{An eight-card fit is never guaranteed by a Spiral raise, so before raising to game responder asks the cheapest step and lets opener confess whether the support is three trumps or four.
[BID 1D] @S @v(open|opens) 1\D — a 12-to-14 opener with no five-card major, so the longer minor; nothing is promised in the majors yet.
[BID 1H] @S @v(show|shows) four or more \H and at least invitational values, staying low so the spiral has room.
[BID 2H] @S @v(agree|agrees) \H, but the raise can be three- or four-card support, so it opens a description rather than setting the level.
[BID 2S] @S @v(ask|asks) with the spiral 2\S — artificial and forcing, requesting trump length, strength, and any shortness.
[BID 2N] 2NT is the lowest coded step, not natural: @S @v(show|shows) only three-card support, balanced, with a minimum and no shortness.
[show NS] South's \HKT8 backed North's \HJ765 only three deep, a flat 4-3 with no ruff in sight, so the coded minimum kept the auction in 2NT rather than a heart partscore. Eight tricks came home for plus 120 — exactly the modest result a flat minimum should expect.}
