[BID 1D] @S @v(open|opens) 1\D — a 12-to-14 opener with no five-card major, so the longer minor; nothing is promised in the majors yet.
[BID 1H] @S @v(show|shows) four or more \H and at least invitational values, staying low so the spiral has room.
[BID 2H] @S @v(agree|agrees) \H, but the raise can be three- or four-card support, so it opens a description rather than setting the level.
[BID 2S] @S @v(ask|asks) with the spiral 2\S — artificial and forcing, requesting trump length, strength, and any shortness.
[BID 3D] 3\D is a coded step, not a natural rebid: @S @v(show|shows) three-card support with shortness in the other minor (\C), a ruffing value rather than a flat hand.
[BID 4H] [ACCEPT 3N] The ruffing value adds a trick, so @S @v(bid|bids) 4\H; on this slim 25-count, however, 3NT is equally defensible.
[show NS] South's \HA72 gave only three-card support, but the singleton \C8 opposite North's \HKJT4 supplied the club ruff that turns 25 points into ten tricks. 4\H delivered plus 420; 3NT would have been the cautious road, but the shortness justified the 4-3 game.}
